<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06016150 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06016150 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Karen T. Borchers -- Mercury News; MONITORING THE GULF SITUATION-- Marsha Stewart of Milpitas watches television for the latest developmentson the Persian Gulf crisis. Her son is a paratrooper in Saudi Arabia.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  MIDEAST; WAR; IRAQ; AID; LIST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  If your group plans events or provides assistance related to the Persian Gulfcrisis, send the information to the Mercury News City Desk, 750 Ridder ParkDrive, San Jose 95190, or by fax, (408) 288-8060. We also would like yoursuggestions on other services that should be listed.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CRISIS IN THE GULFWHAT YOU CAN DO  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Crisis in the GulfSee also related stories on pages 1A and 13-16A of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>  Status of military personnel; American Red Cross: (408) 292-6242; The 24-hourtelephone line is provided at no cost to service personnel and their immediatefamilies by the Red Cross, the only organization recognized by the military asa conduit for messages to and from members of the military and their families.The service is intended for information about births, deaths and other familyemergencies. Red Cross chapters in Palo Alto and San Francisco also providecounseling and have available interest-free loans and grants for urgentpersonal crises involving family members, providing certain qualifications aremet.;    The U.S. Department of Defense has no central number for people toinquire about personnel deployed in Operation Desert Shield. When there arecasualties, the military establishes families-only, toll-free 800 numbers tofind out whether relatives are OK. The military provides these numbers to thefamilies and gives them to CNN as soon as they are set up -- generally rightafter there have been casualties. In a crisis, the Navy office in SanFrancisco will provide information about family members at (415) 395-5190.;Status of Arab families; Silicon Valley Congress of Arab Americans:; 3424Victor St., Santa Clara 95054, (408) 980-8736; The group, to a limited extent,will help track down people in Arab countries for relatives and friends. Theoffice is staffed part-time on weekdays.; Military family support; Familysupport centers, established at most military bases, provide counseling fordependents -- spouses and children -- of soldiers stationed at those bases.They are not meant for parents, but they sometimes can offer parents who aresearching for children stationed overseas guidance about where to beginlooking.; Family Liaison Office: (800) 833-6622 Monday-Friday, 4:30 a.m.-2p.m. PST; Families of Army personnel; Fort Ord: (408) 242-4580; Monterey:(408) 646-3060; Oakland Army Base: (415) 466-2508; The Presidio in SanFrancisco:; (415) 561-6090; Families of Navy personnel; Moffett: (415)404-8066; Alameda: (415) 263-3146; San Francisco: (415) 395-5176; Vallejo:(707) 646-2527; Families also can find the family support center nearest themby calling:; The Army: (800) 542-9254; Army Reserves: (800) 874-8451; MarineCorps, collect: (619) 725-5361; Navy: Family Service Center, Norfolk (Va.)NAS, (800) 372-5463; Coast Guard: (800) 283-8724; Families also may use thisnumber for referral or assistance.; Operation Yellow Ribbon:; (800) 488-6288;Operation Yellow Ribbon is operated by families with relatives serving in thePersian Gulf.; American Legion: (800) 786-0901; Use a Touch-Tone phone andleave name, phone number and ZIP code on the recording. Calls are returned byrepresentatives from American Legion regional offices who assess the familymember's situation and locate appropriate local assistance for problemsranging from family crises to home maintenance. Services are available only tofamilies of service members assigned to duty in the Persian Gulf.; Blooddonations; American Red Cross: (408) 292-6242; Central Valley Chapter:; (408)292-6242; The Red Cross collects blood on behalf of the military in additionto community needs. The group has met the military's current needs, and theDepartment of Defense has a stockpile of blood, so there is no immediatecrisis. The Red Cross cannot earmark blood for Operation Desert Shield, butthe group will make sure all the blood needed for Saudi Arabia is sent there,while at the same time making sure that the local community's needs are met.;   The Central Valley Chapter -- which includes Santa Clara, Santa Cruz, SanBenito and Monterey counties -- is putting together a list of donors in theevent of a crisis. To add your name to the list, telephone the chapter.Prospective donors will be contacted as the need arises. Volunteers are alwayswelcome to help during blood drives.; Mailings to U.S. troops; The genericaddress for people stationed on land in Operation Desert Shield is:; AnyServicemember; Operation Desert Shield; APO New York 09848-0006; The genericaddress for people stationed on ships in Operation Desert Shield is:; AnyServicemember; Operation Desert Shield; FPO New York 09866-0006; The militarysupplies troops with the basics, including sunscreen and soap. But servicepeople always can use care packages full of toiletries, including brand-namesoap that is better than military soap. Check with your local post office forcustoms restrictions, and there is a list at your local post office of thingsyou cannot send to Saudi Arabia in particular for religious and culturalreasons.;    Mail sent to soldiers taking part in Operation Desert Shield mustconform to regulations for domestic mail -- which limit mail to a maximum of108 inches in combined length and girth and 70 pounds. Senders must completeCustoms Form 2966A.; Desert Fax; For locations, information: (800) 555-8111;Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and ATandamp;T established a fax line for people tosend messages to participants in Operation Desert Shield. Fax machines are setup at many ATandamp;T stores. You can fax up to two pages to anyone, provided youknow his or her first and last name, rank, military address and SocialSecurity number. To find out the ATandamp;T store with a fax machine nearest you,call the 800 number from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through Friday and 8 a.m. to4 p.m. Saturday.; Arab-American groups; Islamic Education and InformationCenter:;  325 North Third St., San Jose, (408) 942-8154 or (408) 947-9389;Silicon Valley Congress of Arab Americans:; 3424 Victor St., Santa Clara95054, (408) 980-8736; American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee:;  4201Connecticut Ave., N.W., Suite 500, Washington, D.C. 20008, (202) 244-2990;These organizations can provide advice and other help to people who havesuffered ethnic discrimination.; Jewish groups; Jewish Community RelationsCouncil of Greater San Jose:; 14855 Oka Road, Los Gatos, (408) 358-3033;Jewish Community Relations Council of Palo Alto:; 655 Arastradero Road, Suite100, Palo Alto, (415) 493-5413; Jewish Community Relations Council of SanFrancisco:; 121 Steuart St., San Francisco 94105, (415) 957-1551; JewishFamily Service:; 14855 Oka Road, Los Gatos, (408) 356-7576; Jewish Family andChildren's Services:; 480 California Ave., Palo Alto, (415) 326-6696; Theseorganizations can provide advice and other help to people who have sufferedethnic discrimination, or to people with family and friends in Israel.;Military recruiting; Army: (800) USA-ARMY (872-2769); Navy: (800) 252-0559;Air Force: (800) 423-8723; Selective Service System: (708) 688-6888, from 6a.m. to 2 p.m. PST; The Army and Navy numbers can provide information aboutrecruiting centers near you. The U.S. Government listings in the front of thewhite pages of your phone book also contain locations and phone numbers forrecruiting centers. The Air Force number is for people who want informationabout joining the service. The Selective Service number is only for specificquestions about registration.; Peace groups; Mountain View Voices for Peace:;(415) 961-8918; Interfaith Peace Coalition:; (408) 297-4668; Peninsula PeaceCenter:; (415) 326-8837 or (415) 327-3223; San Jose Peace Center:; (408)297-2299; American Friends Service Committee, San Francisco: (415) 752-7766;Beyond War, Palo Alto: (415) 328-7756; Persian Gulf Peace Coalition, SantaCruz: (408) 458-0276; Elected officials; White House comment office:; (202)456-1111; Congress: (202) 224-3121.; Letters may be sent to U.S. House ofRepresentatives, Washington, D.C. 20515, or U.S. Senate, Washington, D.C.20510.; Events; Today; Capitola: Weekly vigil from 10 a.m. to noon everyWednesday at intersection of Bay and Capitola avenues, across from Gayle'sBakery.; Los Gatos: Rally at 5 p.m. at at the park at Santa Cruz Avenue andEast Main Street, near the Los Gatos post office.; Santa Cruz: Paneldiscussion of what to do about a military draft, featuring draft experts andVietnam veterans, from 7:30 p.m. to 9:30 p.m., Pacific Cultural Center, 1307Seabright Ave.; Thursday; Livermore: A multi-faith religious service conductedjointly by Muslim, Jewish, Catholic, Protestant and Hindu clergy will be heldat 7 p.m. at St. Michael's Catholic Church, 458 Maple St. Scripture readingsin Arabic, Hebrew, Latin, Spanish and Sanskrit.; Saturday; San Francisco:Protest march at Mission Dolores Park at 10:30 a.m., concluding with a CivicCenter Rally at 1 p.m.; Jan. 26; San Francisco: March at 10:30 a.m. at JustinHerman Plaza, ending with a Civic Center rally.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Compiled by Mercury News Staff Writer Gwynne Young  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910116  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  1,484  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday January 16, 199100016150,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  0  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>